								<blockquote>Quote<br><hr>Factions! <BR>By: -Phreak- <BR><BR>Factions are defined as an "in game group or party". The idea of a faction significantly adds to the fun-factor of SWG. You have your own group of people, all brought together for a sole purpose of domination. Factions provide a sense of competition, like who can get more cities and planets than the other. You also have a clear-cut enemy in the universe, which is helpful in PvP because it tells who you attack and who you shake hands with.<BR><BR>At release of SWG, only the Rebel Alliance and Galactic Empire will be available to join but there will be more factions available later, like the Hutt criminal empire. I suspect the smugglers and bounty hunters and the like will have a haven here. To join a faction, you talk to an NPC for the desired faction. Sounds easy, huh? Well don't forget that you will have to deal with battling the opposite faction and watching where you go. If you don't want to have those problems everyday, you may stay unaffiliated. You would be a mercenary if you preferred to do that. Also, if you have a friend in the enemy faction, then you may chat with him/her even though you really shouldn't talk with the foe.<BR><BR>When you go to talk to the faction recruiter, he may give you a task to earn "faction points". You gain these points by doing certain actions for the desired faction, and when you reach a specific amount, then you may be eligible for membership in the given party. An example of a faction-point-gaining mission would be to assassinate a character of another faction. You can also acquire more points when you are in the faction by simply visiting the battlefield. Another function of faction points is that you can spend them on military training, which in turn leads to XP and new skills which you would not have been able to access before. Sooner or later, faction points may also be used to purchase automatic defenses, walls, and turrets to use on your city. <BR><BR>One of the main benefits of being in a faction is that you can control NPC's. If you are on the Imperial side, then you can manage things like Stormtroopers. You would control these like controlling a pet, which can be better explained in Kaelic II's thread about Vehicles and Pets. Some factions may control entire planets, but don't worry, players of the opposing factions may find missions and visit these planets. Other perks of being in a certain faction is that you may use special military equipment specific to the faction. For example, if you are in the Galactic Empire, then you have AT-ST's or Tie's available to you. The more faction points that you have, the more abilities you have, obviously. You may obtain special military uniforms and rank titles according to your faction, as well. Some of these perks come from spending Faction Points. Different species will have more trouble advancing in rank though, for example a Wookie would have to do more work than someone in the Galactic Empire. <BR><BR>In the faction, you choose to be Covert or Declared. Declared members have the ability to attack any enemy they see at any time, and are viable to attack at any time as well. They are also allowed to build structures for the faction at any time. Covert members, however, cannot attack enemies outright. They can assist members of their faction (healing them, for example) during a battle, though. When helping out a faction member, their alignment is briefly revealed and an enemy can attack them. <BR><BR>Another way to have clear-cut enemies and a "small faction" is if a Player Association (P.A.) is made. The P.A. chooses its enemies and whom it is at war with, and is similar to being declared as a faction. <BR><BR>Each faction will have its own advantages (like different star ships and different kind of troops). I'm sure that the factions will be somewhat equal though, in terms of Missions and equipment. I would probably choose being in the Galactic Empire because I like the Storm Troopers' look over the Rebel Troopers' look, but then again, I'm weird.<BR><hr></blockquote> 
